reasoning:
First off, Google (GOOG) lies outside my circle of competence. I like simple, predictable consumer franchises – Coca-Cola, See’s Candies, Apple as a consumer play – and I steer clear of the complex algorithms, regulatory challenges, and rapid technology shifts that define a business like Google.

On the moat front, there’s no denying Google’s search algorithm, advertising network, Android ecosystem, and YouTube give it formidable advantages. It’s like owning the tollbooth at the busiest highway in the world. But a strong moat alone doesn’t get me to invest if I can’t truly understand the bugs, bots, and board-level oversight required to keep it intact.

Management under Sundar Pichai is clearly capable – Alphabet’s capital allocation into AI, YouTube, and cloud shows strategic thinking – but I have no detailed data here to evaluate insider integrity or long-term incentives. In the past, I’ve backed founders like Warren McColl at Coca-Cola and David Sokol at BNSF because I knew them. Google’s leadership is a bit of a black box to me.

Financially, we have no numbers in the packet – no earnings consistency, no debt levels, no cash flow breakdown. What I do know from public filings is that Alphabet has grown revenues for decades, generates cash like a river, and keeps debt low. But ‘insufficient data’ is all this model gives me.

Valuation? No intrinsic-value estimate, no margin of safety. A wonderful business at an unknown price is not enough. I want to know exactly what I’m paying for each dollar of earnings.

Over the next 20 years, the world will search, watch videos, and run businesses online, and Google will likely play a central role. Yet I’d rather own a great consumer operation at a fair price than a fine tech franchise at an unknown price.

Compared to opportunities in my portfolio – banks trading below book value, brand franchises like Coca-Cola or Apple with clear margins of safety, or our railroad that I understand inside-out – Google simply doesn’t fit my approach. When in doubt, I say ‘no.’
